  footnotes: []
english:
  title: On the Nature of Ci Poetry
  author: Lee Seok
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The fu form arose in recent times, tracing its source to the Three Weft-texts, which transformed into the Sao, and only after the Sao did fu composition begin. Ci emerged from the Confucian tradition—the Hexagram Statements that serve to illuminate the Book of Changes. Yet reading these ci verses today, one finds abundant use of rhyme, suggesting they too descend from the "Responsive Verses" of the Classic of Documents.

    Quick Guan of Chu composed the Sao, a variation upon the transformed elegance of antiquity. Song Yu, Jing Cha, and Jia Yi arose in succession, establishing fu composition, completing its lineage. When the Han rose, Emperor Wu crafted the Autumn Wind Verse, grounded in the Sao yet rendered in language more refined and austere. The recluse Tao Yuanming of Jin wrote the Return to the Fields Verse—elaborate in expression yet more economical than fu itself. When Ban Gu and Sima Xiangru emerged, they encompassed all without remainder, giving rise to the saying that one poem required ten years to complete. Alas, we marvel at such achievement, yet lament it too.

    Nor is this peculiar to literature alone. What adorns the surface grows daily, while what dwells within diminishes. Branches flourish while roots weaken—a strange paradox indeed. Yet should the roots run strong, what harm if the branches grow sparse? What harm at all?
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The Three Weft-texts (三緯) refer to apocryphal commentaries on Confucian classics, believed in medieval East Asia to contain esoteric wisdom about poetry and language.
  - key: ''
    value: The Sao (騷) tradition, exemplified by Qu Yuan's 'Lament,' represents a crucial turning point in Chinese literary history, moving from classical elegance toward more personal, emotional expression.
  - key: ''
    value: Ban Gu and Sima Xiangru were celebrated Han Dynasty fu masters whose elaborate compositions set new standards for the form, though at the cost of accessibility.
